WEBVTT

00:03.862 --> 00:05.364
This sort of set the groundwork. We became the 
official research agency for the Texas Highway

00:05.464 --> 00:08.828
Department. Most of our, well, all of our early 
funding was from the Texas Highway Department.

00:14.595 --> 00:18.981
That was our only source of funds.

00:19.001 --> 00:22.345
So this started in 1956 when I came. Now this was the 
same time that the, or shortly after I got here,

00:22.425 --> 00:32.417
later on that fall, they passed the federal 
National Congress passed the Highway Revenue Act

00:33.578 --> 00:46.175
of 1956, which was the creation of the interstate 
system, the national system of interstate and

00:33.578 --> 00:46.175
defense highways.

00:48.558 --> 01:02.337
As a part of that, they created what they called a 
research and planning, highway research and

00:48.558 --> 01:02.337
planning fund stream off of the special taxations 
that were set up to fund The interstate system.

01:05.991 --> 01:21.671
Now, the interstate system was funded from 
special taxes that were levied $0.05 a gallon

01:05.991 --> 01:21.671
against all gasoline, plus taxes on tires and 
lubricating oils and spare parts. This went into a

01:23.673 --> 01:28.219
trust fund held at the national level. Out of the 
trust fund, monies were apportioned on a formula

01:33.130 --> 01:35.553
basis to individual states. Now, 1.5% of each 
state's apportionment was eligible for

01:36.715 --> 01:47.990
expenditure on planning activities and 
research. Now, this really sort of created the

01:49.533 --> 01:57.163
research activities in highway transportation.

01:59.708 --> 02:09.502
However, that law said that if those funds were not 
spent on planning or research activities, they

01:59.708 --> 02:09.502
could revert to construction. And the state could 
go ahead and use them for construction. So 1.5% of

02:14.289 --> 02:23.862
the income stream to each state off the trust fund 
was a substantial amount of money.

02:27.908 --> 02:29.310
And it stimulated some. expansion in the research 
programs, particularly in areas of materials and

02:29.611 --> 02:44.429
what I'd call hard research, bridge work, piers, 
structural work. Then as the interstate began to

02:45.390 --> 02:53.239
actually go in to get into being in the late 50s, 
there became a growing awareness of the social and

02:55.143 --> 03:04.196
economic problems that were being created by it. 
One of the first early problem areas was the

03:06.479 --> 03:11.547
problem of bypassing small towns.

03:14.471 --> 03:24.205
There was a great concern that if the interstate 
system bypassed a small community, that that

03:14.471 --> 03:24.205
community would wither and die. since it was no 
longer now had the through traffic to support it.

03:29.481 --> 03:37.971
So that generated a series of studies on the 
economic consequences of bypasses, and that was

03:29.481 --> 03:37.971
some of the earlier work that we did. And our group 
then became a department head in TTI over the

03:38.992 --> 03:48.444
economics and planning department.

03:51.247 --> 03:53.770
And I believe we had four departments at that time. 
And

03:55.268 --> 03:59.693
that's not right. First, Bill Atkins, Dr. William 
G. Atkins, who is now retired from the system, was

04:01.535 --> 04:10.825
head of that group. And I worked under him. Then in 
the late 50s, he left. to go complete his PhD

04:24.884 --> 04:27.747
degree. And I became head of that group. And when he 
completed his PhD, he came back and worked for me

04:32.212 --> 04:36.196
then. We just sort of switched roles. But in 1964 
then, with the Revenue Act of 64, they changed what

04:39.941 --> 04:54.857
we call the HPR funding formula, the Highway 
Planning and Research Fund.

04:57.723 --> 05:16.069
Now the states that did not spend that 1.5% rather 
than having it available to revert to their

04:57.723 --> 05:16.069
construction program where most of them had been 
using it and very little of it going into planning

04:57.723 --> 05:16.069
and research activities, Texas was one of the few 
states that were using substantial amounts of it.

05:18.226 --> 05:20.750
I said, you either use it or lose it. If you don't use 
it for those activities, then it reverts back to

05:21.051 --> 05:27.382
the federal government and will become a part of 
the reapportionment process. They'll

05:27.422 --> 05:29.265
reapportion it to states that do need it. So that 
stimulated a substantial new activity in

05:30.387 --> 05:38.060
research and planning. And really, our program 
grew rather rapidly after 1964.

05:47.150 --> 05:56.562
In the meantime, I had been taking coursework 
toward a PhD, again in agricultural economics,

05:47.150 --> 05:56.562
again under Dr. McNeely. And I

05:57.964 --> 06:05.634
can't even remember when I finished it. I had to 
look at the bio data sheet. I want to say 1965. I

06:09.699 --> 06:12.803
don't think it's right. It must have been because 
you're only allowed 10 years to get it done. Oh, I

06:16.914 --> 06:19.778
broke all sorts of rules when I was doing it. I 
didn't have a formal program set up until after I'd

06:21.099 --> 06:28.749
been taking courses for a long time. Then I filed a 
degree plan. But I also ran into the problem that

06:31.532 --> 06:43.347
the university then had a regulation that anyone 
with a rank greater than assistant professor

06:31.532 --> 06:43.347
could not get a terminal degree here. Well, I got 
special dispensation because I had been hired

06:46.448 --> 06:58.023
with the proviso that I would be able to do it to 
complete the degree. So I'm one of the few people

06:58.984 --> 07:07.634
that ever received a degree from A&M carrying the 
rank of associate. And it was because I had been

07:12.520 --> 07:17.987
contracted to do that, or it was in our agreement 
that I would be able to complete a degree. Well, let

07:19.769 --> 07:20.730
me ask you this. You said that Texas was one of the 
states that put a lot of money into research on

07:21.311 --> 07:26.437
highways. Is it some of the states that have poorer 
transportation systems, did they fail to use this

07:28.179 --> 07:34.186
research? For instance, Louisiana and New 
Mexico, their road systems in those two states are

07:40.195 --> 07:43.679
not up to par with those in Texas for the most part. 
Were those two states not using that money for

07:43.719 --> 07:47.224
research? They were not. In fact, many states were 
not. Many states still don't use much of it for

07:49.987 --> 07:53.151
research. It can be used for research or planning. 
Now, in recent years, federal planning

07:56.876 --> 08:07.249
requirements have gotten ever increasingly 
stringent, so they've been required to do more and

07:56.876 --> 08:07.249
more planning activities. which have required a 
greater and greater percentage of the combined

08:07.938 --> 08:14.287
research and planning budgets. So many research 
budgets that you work on, this doesn't just apply

08:15.308 --> 08:22.357
to the interstate center, it applies to all the 
state highways. Oh, yeah, right. No, the funding

08:23.859 --> 08:26.964
is just out of that interstate funding stream. I 
get the impression from that that probably

08:27.344 --> 08:33.152
California was definitely using the money for 
research and planning. Texas were? What were some

08:34.467 --> 08:37.191
of the other states that were that you know of? Oh, 
Pennsylvania did, New York that had, and Indiana

08:37.211 --> 08:44.863
through Purdue. Most states, now California is an 
exception, but most states do not have an

08:46.325 --> 08:56.140
on-board, a major on-board research capability.

08:58.544 --> 09:02.650
So they do their research through their 
universities or consultants or some other way.

09:05.789 --> 09:11.037
California does have its own in-house research 
program. Now, Texas doesn't have much of one. We

09:13.281 --> 09:17.447
and the University of Texas do most of theirs. They 
do a little bit, but, oh, 10% of what we do. I thought

09:21.854 --> 09:25.700
this TTI was meeting that requirement that you 
said there. It is. Now, back in 19...

09:33.173 --> 09:55.435
late 50s and I'm not sure just what time we 
developed what we call the cooperative research

09:33.173 --> 09:55.435
program with the highway department that means 
and this is a unique

09:33.173 --> 09:55.435
arrangement among state departments and 
universities and that we're the only one that

09:33.173 --> 09:55.435
really has this sort of an arrangement the 
University of Texas then came into it in about

09:56.849 --> 09:59.291
1968. They also developed the same sort of 
agreement with the University of Texas. But this

10:05.296 --> 10:18.328
is a system whereby we jointly get together with 
the department and with their district engineers

10:05.296 --> 10:18.328
and determine what sorts of research needs to be 
done in the coming year. And in the spring of the

10:19.329 --> 10:25.354
year, we formulate a research program to begin in 
September in the beginning of the new fiscal year.

10:28.475 --> 10:48.575
And we have an agreement with the department that 
we will try to keep this in a sort of a constant mode

10:28.475 --> 10:48.575
in terms of total amount of money available for 
